The Meru government will release Sh135 million for bursaries this year and 92 students will be awarded scholarships from form one to four.Education chief officer David Bariu said the county government has set aside Sh3 million for each of the 45 wards and slots for 92 more students in the scholarship programme started last year by Governor Peter Munya.We have so far distributed Sh360 million in bursaries, he said.Bariu said the county does not want needy students missing lessons or dropping out of school for lack of fees.&ldquo;The programme has helped many vulnerable students,&rdquo; he said.Speaking in his office, Bariu urged parents to also take their children to technical training centres and polytechnics. &ldquo;Vision 2030 cannot be implemented by white collar jobs only,&rdquo; he said.